  <section class="container-fluid main-content">
    <h2>CSS3 "Stable" Examples</h2>
    <p>My examples of my <a href="/html-css/examples">HTML/CSS production pages</a> include many CSS "Stable" examples. Below are examples of "Stable" CSS that are not in those examples.</p>
    <ul class="bulleted">
      <li>
        <h3><a href="javascript:;" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#backgroundsAndBorders" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="backgroundsAndBorders">Backgrounds and Borders Level 3</a></h3>
        <div class="collapse in" id="backgroundsAndBorders">
          <div class="well">
            <ul class="linear-gradient">
              <h4>Background: Linear gradient</h4>
              <li>
                <span class="top-to-bottom">
                  <p>Top to bottom</p>
                </span>
                <span class="left-to-right">
                  <p>Left to right</p>
                </span>
                <span class="diagonal-to-right">
                  <p>Diagonal to right</p>
                </span>
                <span class="angle">
                  <p>25 degree angle</p>
                </span>
                <span class="multiple-stops">
                  <p>Multiple color stops</p>
                </span>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <ul class="border-example">
              <h4>Background: Borders</h4>
              <li>
                <span class="rounded-corners-color">
                  <p>Rounded corners with background color</p>
                </span>
                <span class="oval">
                  <p>Empty oval</p>
                </span>
                <span class="circle">
                  <p>Circle with image</p>
                </span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3><a href="javascript:;" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#conditionalRules" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="conditionalRules">Conditional Rules Level 3</a></h3>
        <div class="collapse" id="conditionalRules">
          <div class="well">
            <p>This page has CSS conditional rules for the screen width and for print.</p>
            <ul class="bulleted">
              <li>Squeeze the browser width to see the content disappear and a message disappear.</li>
              <li>Do a print preview to see the content in a narrower column.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3><a href="javascript:;" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#multiColumnLayout" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="multiColumnLayout">Multi-column Layout</a></h3>
        <div class="collapse" id="multiColumnLayout">
          <div class="well">
            <p class="multicolumns">
              This is an HTML paragraph that has been formatted as three columns using the column-count CSS rule. (I wish I would have had this when I wrote the <a href="/html-css/examples">FamilySearch.org Production Examples</a> several years ago). The CSS rule column-gap is used to determine the space between the columns. The CSS rule column-rule can be used to specify a line or rule between the columns.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3><a href="javascript:;" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#valuesAndUnits" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="valuesAndUnits">Values and Units Level 3</a></h3>
        <div class="collapse" id="valuesAndUnits">
          <div class="well">
            <p>It used to be that we just used the measurements "px" and "%" for font-size and other CSS size rules. Many years ago we got excited about using "em" for styles that were a bit easier to adjust by just changing the top level size on the html or body tags.</p>
            <p>Here are the current relative units: em, ex, ch, rem, vw, vh, vmin, and vmax. You can get an explanation of each here: <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_units.asp">http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_units.asp</a>. At FamilySearch.org we are using the "rem" measurement which is relative to the font-size of the root element.</p>
            <p>The items in the following list have a font-size of 1.6rem:</p>
            <ul class="rem-example">
              <li>The default size of this page's html font-size is 10px. This results in a font-size of 16px for these items.</li>
              <li>To see that the items' font-size changes to 25.6px when the font-size of the html is changes to 16px, <button onclick="document.getElementsByTagName('html')[0].style.fontSize='16px'">click here</button>.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3><a href="javascript:;" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#cascadingAndInheritance" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="cascadingAndInheritance">Cascading and Inheritance Level 3</a></h3>
        <div class="collapse" id="cascadingAndInheritance">
          <div class="well cascading-inheritance">
            <p>One of the new properties that affects cascading/inheritance is the "all" property. New value are the "initial" and "inherit" values.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>This will inherit the 18px font size and blue font color that is specified for the parent div element.</li>
              <li class="initial-value">This will get the 18px font size from the parent div element, but the font color is set to "initial" so it will be black.</li>
              <li class="inherit-value"></li>
              <li class="all-property">This won't inherit anything from the immediate parent or any other parent because it has the property "all" set to "initial". It doesn't even have the margin or padding of an unordered list item.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
